 termination criterion based on the effective sample size. The new-born particles produced by resampling operations are helpful in alleviating particle degeneracy, whereas particles free from being resampled is conducive to improving the diversity of particles. Thus, a tradeoff between these two problems can be achieved. Also, two techniques, that is, recursive computation of the effective sample size and improved bisection method, for improving the computational efficiency are proposed. Simulation results conducted on two typical examples show the improved performance of the proposed method.", "references": [], "authors": [{"country": null, "city": null, "name": " Junyi Zuo", "affiliation": "Sch. of Aeronaut., Northwestern Polytech. Univ., Xi'an, China", "university": null}], "publisher": "IET", "citations": [], "Metrics": {"Downloads (6 weeks) ": null, "Downloads (cumulative)": null, "Downloads (12 months)": null, "Citation Count": null}, "title": "Dynamic resampling for alleviating sample impoverishment of particle filter", "arnumber": "6684261"}, "Article 6": {"doi": "10.1049/iet-rsn.2012.0330", "keywords": [{"type": "INSPEC: Controlled Indexing", "kwd": ["synthetic aperture radar", "radar imaging", "radar receivers", "radar transmitters", "satellite navigation"]}, {"type": "INSPEC: Non-Controlled Indexing", "kwd": ["passive bistatic synthetic aperture radar imaging", "theoretically predicted parameters", "system technical feasibility", "ground moving vehicle", "Galileo satellite emissions", "navigation satellites", "experimental demonstration", "moving receiver", "Galileo transmitters"]}], "abstract": "This study discusses experimental methods and results on passive bistatic synthetic aperture radar using navigation satellites as transmitters of opportunity and a moving receiver. The article highlights practical issues in imaging. Experimental imagery obtained using Galileo satellite emissions and a receiver onboard a ground moving vehicle confirm the system te